<node><name>Introduce Activity</name>
<id>3</id>
<lefticon>undefined</lefticon>
<righticon>orchestration</righticon>
<column>ICI</column>
<textHTML>&lt;p&gt;Assign students to groups of 3-4.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Give each group 27 cards, each of which has a problem on it&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;These cards correspond to the three sets of problems (9 each) used in the Problem Sorting activity&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;Note: Ideally these cards are provided on interactive whiteboards in a notebook file, however physical printed cards can also work.&lt;/p&gt;</textHTML>
<linkedwf>undefined</linkedwf>
<textheight>184</textheight>
<tagARRAY/>
</node>
<node><name>Categorize Problems</name>
<id>4</id>
<lefticon>group</lefticon>
<righticon>analyze</righticon>
<column>ICS</column>
<textHTML>&lt;p&gt;Sort the problems into categories of own choosing.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Note: This decision should be made based on the physics in the problem, not on superficial grounds. There is no correct answer here: the justification is more important.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</textHTML>
<linkedwf>undefined</linkedwf>
<textheight>124</textheight>
<tagARRAY/>
</node>
<node><name>Justify Categorization</name>
<id>12</id>
<lefticon>group</lefticon>
<righticon>write</righticon>
<column>ICS</column>
<textHTML>&lt;p&gt;Provide a written rationale for the chosen groupings, explaining why these particular categories are chosen and why they are physically significant.&lt;/p&gt;</textHTML>
<linkedwf>undefined</linkedwf>
<textheight>100</textheight>
